11 The /etc/os-release Resets when base-files updates. to prevent that, you can mark base-files as held sudo apt-mark hold base-files
12 Remove /etc/update-motd.d with sudo rm -rf /etc/update-motd.d then sudo reboot
13 Run sudo apt-mark hold desktop-base
14 You May Stop The Services Of Snap
   sudo systemctl stop snapd
   sudo systemctl disable snapd

  Purge Snapd (Recommended For Older Hardware Or Any Slow Hardware)
  sudo apt purge snapd

  Clean Up Leftover Directories
  rm -rf ~/snap
  sudo rm -rf /var/snap /var/lib/snapd /var/cache/snapd

  Autoremove
  sudo apt autoremove

  Reboot
  sudo reboot

  System Updates: Ubuntu may reinstall Snapd during major upgrades. To prevent this, you can block Snapd from being reinstalled:
  sudo apt-mark hold snapd
